data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed**. The provider only supports asynchronous I/O natively, and the shim that let you call synchronous methods is gone.

**All four methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:**

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Fix

Convert the repository to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; no I/O occurs until `SaveChangesAsync()`.
- Callers must be updated to `await` these methods, which propagates `async` up the call stack (controllers, services, etc.).
- The `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` namespace provides the `Async` extension methods — no new packages needed.
